00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:50.570
You are half.

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:53.300
Their Japanese friends were
telling them, you are only half

00:14:53.300 --> 00:14:54.290
of what we were doing.

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:56.845
Well, don't you know?

00:14:56.845 --> 00:15:00.970
I was prepared for that.

00:15:00.970 --> 00:15:04.530
They came home and
said, we are just half.

00:15:04.530 --> 00:15:06.836
Well-- so Benjamin
is my oldest son.

00:15:06.836 --> 00:15:08.210
Micah is my younger
son-- I said,

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:10.030
let me ask you some questions.

00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:12.690
When you go to
Japanese school, do you

00:15:12.690 --> 00:15:14.170
understand your
Japanese teacher?

00:15:14.170 --> 00:15:15.710
Well--

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:18.221
Do you understand
the comic books?

00:15:18.221 --> 00:15:19.970
Do you understand the
books that you read?

00:15:19.970 --> 00:15:21.000
Well, yes.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.420
How about when you watch
Japanese on the TV?

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:24.160
Can you follow?

00:15:24.160 --> 00:15:25.039
Yes, I can do that.

00:15:25.039 --> 00:15:26.330
Now, do you like Japanese food?

00:15:26.330 --> 00:15:27.038
Well, sure we do.

00:15:27.038 --> 00:15:28.455
Sure we do.

00:15:28.455 --> 00:15:29.431
And what about Grandma?

00:15:29.431 --> 00:15:30.930
Can you talk to
Grandma in Japanese?

00:15:30.930 --> 00:15:32.415
Well, of course, I can.

00:15:32.415 --> 00:15:34.650
I said, what about
when you go to America?

00:15:34.650 --> 00:15:36.650
When you go to America,
can you do those things?

00:15:36.650 --> 00:15:37.850
Do you eat American food?

00:15:37.850 --> 00:15:38.349
Yeah.

00:15:38.349 --> 00:15:39.750
Do you like American books?

00:15:39.750 --> 00:15:40.250
Yeah.

00:15:40.250 --> 00:15:41.856
And do you watch
American television?

00:15:41.856 --> 00:15:43.230
Yeah, I like all
of these things.

00:15:43.230 --> 00:15:45.380
And can you pay with
American friends?

00:15:45.380 --> 00:15:47.376
Yes, yes, I can do
all of those things.

00:15:47.376 --> 00:15:48.500
And how about your grandma?

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:50.820
Can you talk to your grandma and
grandpa in America in English?

00:15:50.820 --> 00:15:51.890
Well, of course, we can.

00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:53.380
Yes, we can.

00:15:53.380 --> 00:15:55.450
So now, let's go back to Japan.

00:15:55.450 --> 00:15:57.700
And we go back to Japan.

00:15:57.700 --> 00:15:59.090
How about your Japanese friends?

00:15:59.090 --> 00:16:00.690
Can they eat Japanese food?

00:16:00.690 --> 00:16:02.050
Well, yeah.

00:16:02.050 --> 00:16:04.670
Can they watch Japanese
television-- yeah-- and so one

00:16:04.670 --> 00:16:05.220
and so on.

00:16:05.220 --> 00:16:10.680
So what about when your
Japanese friends go to America?

00:16:10.680 --> 00:16:13.410
Can they watch
American television?

00:16:13.410 --> 00:16:14.715
No.

00:16:14.715 --> 00:16:16.160
Can they read English books?

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:17.485
No, they cannot do that.

00:16:17.485 --> 00:16:19.110
Can they talk to your
American friends?

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:20.220
No, they can't do that either.

00:16:20.220 --> 00:16:21.020
And what about your grandma?

00:16:21.020 --> 00:16:22.853
Will they play with
your grandma in English?

00:16:22.853 --> 00:16:24.690
No, no, they cannot do
any of those things.

00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:29.380
So, I said, Benjamin and
Micah, who is half of whom?

00:16:31.980 --> 00:16:36.080
You see, all of their friends
who had been calling them half,

00:16:36.080 --> 00:16:37.610
they were the half.

00:16:37.610 --> 00:16:40.020
And then, I said, Benjamin
and Micah, I'll tell you what.

00:16:40.020 --> 00:16:41.670
You guys are not half anymore.

00:16:41.670 --> 00:16:44.370
From now on, you're doubles.

00:16:44.370 --> 00:16:46.000
You are doubles.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.380
Well, that was fun.

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:49.920
There was a newsletter.

00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:53.209
Remember people who used to
write and put it on paper

00:16:53.209 --> 00:16:55.000
and put it in mailboxes
and send it around?

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:55.833
Remember those days?

00:16:55.833 --> 00:16:57.205
Maybe some of you don't.

00:16:57.205 --> 00:16:58.500
Yeah, there was that.

00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:02.620
Well, I was a writer for
one of these newsletters

00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:04.050
that traveled throughout Japan.

00:17:04.050 --> 00:17:06.173
And so I wrote about
that experience.

00:17:06.173 --> 00:17:07.839
I wrote about that
day with my children.

00:17:07.839 --> 00:17:08.849
You are not half.

00:17:08.849 --> 00:17:10.300
You're doubles.

00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:11.865
And it went throughout
all of Japan.

00:17:11.865 --> 00:17:16.900
Now, it was not a big group,
but it was the right group.

00:17:16.900 --> 00:17:20.619
Because two weeks later
or three weeks later,

00:17:20.619 --> 00:17:25.790
in a national newspaper, the
country newspaper, there was,

00:17:25.790 --> 00:17:28.670
don't call these
children half anymore.

00:17:28.670 --> 00:17:31.190
Let's call them doubles.

00:17:31.190 --> 00:17:33.630
And suddenly,
everybody in Japan who

00:17:33.630 --> 00:17:35.699
came from two
different countries

00:17:35.699 --> 00:17:36.740
were not half of anybody.

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:38.880
They were double everybody else.

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:40.877
And then about two
weeks after that,

00:17:40.877 --> 00:17:42.460
we're watching
television, and there's

00:17:42.460 --> 00:17:43.840
some singer, [GROWLING],
you know, screaming

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:44.820
and whatever they do.

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:47.660
And the interviewer comes
out--the man he comes out

00:17:47.660 --> 00:17:50.880
with-- and he says, how do you
like being a half in Japan?

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:53.560
He said, don't call me half.

00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:55.490
Call me double.

00:17:55.490 --> 00:17:59.460
And now that word
moves throughout Japan.

00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:02.160
And now, it moves its
way into China, as well.

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:07.110
And I know where that word
came from, because I made it.

00:18:07.110 --> 00:18:07.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:07.610 --> 00:18:09.360
BILL BELEW: It was
never said before then.

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:10.959
I had never heard
it said before then.

00:18:10.959 --> 00:18:13.000
I never knew anybody who
talked like that before.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.630
I never got the
idea from anybody.

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:18.810
I just sat there waiting for
my children to come home.

00:18:18.810 --> 00:18:20.480
I sat there and
waited for my children

00:18:20.480 --> 00:18:24.510
to come home and ask me the
question, why do people call me

00:18:24.510 --> 00:18:26.300
half?

00:18:26.300 --> 00:18:30.784
That's something I
needed to tell them.

00:18:30.784 --> 00:18:32.450
That is something I
needed to tell them.

00:18:32.450 --> 00:18:35.020
And it's not the same as I
want to tell them, is it?

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:36.710
It's not the same.

00:18:36.710 --> 00:18:41.620
So there is another step.

00:18:41.620 --> 00:18:45.127
And this one is things
